readers through a particularly fierce and prolonged set of controversies over patents on life forms linked to important advances in biology and agriculture and potentially life-saving medicines. Comparing battles over patents on animals, human embryonic stem cells, human genes, and plants in the United States and Europe, she shows how political culture, ideology, and history shape patent system politics. Clashes over whose voices and which values matter in the patent system, as well as what counts as knowledge and whose expertise is important, look quite different in these two places. And through these debates, the United States and Europe are developing very different approaches to patent and innovation governance. Not just the first comprehensive look at the controversies swirling around biotechnology patents, Patent Politics is also the first in-depth analysis of the political underpinnings and implications of modern patent systems, and provides a timely analysis of how we can reform these systems around the world to maximize the public interest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aBioethicszEurope. 0aBioethicszUnited States. 0aBiotechnologyxPatents. 0aPatent laws and legislationzEuropexHistory. 0aPatent laws and legislationzUnited StatesxHistory. 4abiotechnology. 4acomparison. 4acontroversy. 4aexpertise. 4ainnovation. 4amorality. 4apatent. 4apolitical culture. 4apolitical ideology. 4ascience and technology policy. 70(DE-601)1041173030(DE-588)4044884-8aPatentrecht2gnd 70(DE-601)1045852340(DE-588)4006791-9aBioethik2gnd 70(DE-601)1046429040(DE-588)4069491-4aBiotechnologie2gnd 70(DE-601)7006345090(DE-588)7864466-5aGentechnikrecht2gnd 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z9783